 test expects both recipes to be selected, but with this change it would only return the first one. The improvement plan actually acknowledges this is an acceptable tradeoff for the rare case of multiple mixed-case titles on a single page, so this test failure might be intentional.\n\nBut the user's requirement is that all existing tests must still pass, which means I need to either skip implementing this position-based tiebreak or make it less aggressive so it doesn't filter out \"Second Recipe\" when it should be included.\n\nLooking at the actual failing case versus the existing test, they're quite different scenarios—one has recipes far apart on the page while the other has them adjacent. I should examine whether the existing test is even testing the right scenario for this improvement.\n\nThe real issue seems to be that the body text line at position 23 is too distant from the title at position 0, so maybe I should focus on letting the word count filter and the Polish cooking verb filter handle this specific case rather than trying to adjust the position tiebreak logic.\n\nI'm realizing there's a tension between keeping existing tests passing and following the improvement plan. Let me look at what that test actually expects to understand if there's a real conflict here. I'm tracing through how the test would behave with the proposed change. With the mock embeddings returning consistent scores for both \"First Recipe\" and \"Second Recipe\", the position factor becomes the deciding factor—and since \"First Recipe\" appears first, it would win the tiebreak, which is actually what the test expects. But I need to verify this logic holds across the scoring calculation to make sure the test passes. Looking at the position factor calculation for \"First Recipe Second Recipe\" at position 0, which gives it a score around 0.896. Now I need to check if it would pass the hard filters—it's a 4-word string with no structural issues, so yes it would. With the multi-title guard in place, there are no ALL_CAPS candidates to select from. When I sort by position, \"First Recipe\" at position 0 comes earliest, and I'm checking which other candidates qualify as close competitors—those at position ≤ 3 with scores exceeding \"First Recipe's\" score of 0.896. \"Second Recipe\" falls short at 0.832, but \"First Recipe Second Recipe\" ties on position and score, so it needs special handling.\n\nThe dedup logic becomes the deciding factor here: since \"First Recipe Second Recipe\" contains \"First Recipe\" as a substring and is longer, the dedup process removes the longer candidate and keeps the shorter one, so \"First Recipe\" survives while \"First Recipe Second Recipe\" gets filtered out.\n\nAfter dedup, I'm left with [\"First Recipe\", \"Second Recipe\"]. When I apply Change 2, the earliest candidate is \"First Recipe\" at position 0, but \"Second Recipe\" scores around 0.832, which falls below the 0.896 threshold needed to qualify as a close competitor. This means the final selection becomes just [\"First Recipe\"], but the test expects both recipes to be included—so implementing Change 2 as described would actually break this test case.\n\nI'm thinking I could modify the approach to only apply the position tiebreak when there's a significant gap between candidates—say, more than 10 positions apart. This would preserve both \"First Recipe\" and \"Second Recipe\" since they're only 1 position apart, while still filtering out distant body text matches. Let me check if this aligns with the improvement plan's intent around handling titles that appear after blank lines or garbled fragments. was filtered). A rigid \"always pick position 0\" would miss these cases. The tolerance of 3 positions allows the algorithm to pick a higher-scoring candidate that's very close to position 0, while still strongly preferring early candidates over body-text lines at positions 20+.\n\nThe 3-position tolerance is for position 0 vs position 1-3. But the plan's logic