iling scenario specifically breaks down.\n\nActually, if Changes 1 and 3 alone filter out those Polish instruction and cooking direction lines before they reach the multi-title guard, the failing scenario would collapse to just one candidate, preventing the multi-title guard from even triggering. That might be enough to fix the regression without needing Change 2.\n\nBut Change 2 would add a safety net against future regressions. The problem is it breaks an existing test. I could modify it to only apply the tiebreak when candidates span more than 10 lines apart—that would handle the regression case while preserving the existing test behavior.\n\nImplementing the distance threshold... Finishing the logic to select the highest-scoring candidate when contamination is detected, then keeping all survivors if the span is small enough—this handles both multi-recipe pages and body-text pollution gracefully.\n\nNow I'm tracing through the actual line positions for the test cases to verify the algorithm works correctly.\n\nLooking at the text structure, I see \"Ingredients\" appears twice as a section header, and the code needs to determine whether to merge it with the recipe names that follow. Since \"Ingredients\" is in the ALWAYS_BLOCK_JOIN_LABELS set, it should be blocked from joining with adjacent lines, which prevents \"Ingredients Pasta Carbonara\" from being treated as a single candidate.\n\nFor \"Pasta Carbonara\" on its own, it passes the initial filters and gets added as a candidate, but when attempting to join it with the ingredient lines below (\"200g pasta\", \"100g guanciale\"), those get filtered out because they match ingredient patterns with compact metrics.\n\n\"Tiramisu Classico\" similarly passes and becomes a candidate. Both candidates have high title similarity in the mock embedding, and since neither is all-caps, the current behavior keeps both of them.\n\nWith my modified Change 2, the span between positions 1 and 5 is 4, which stays within the threshold of 10, so both titles would be retained. This approach also handles the other test cases correctly—joining \"First Recipe\" and \"Second Recipe\" at positions 0 and 1 works since their span is only 1. Now I need to verify this logic against the Smażona zielona fasolka scenario to see what the actual candidate positions are.\n\nLooking at the data, the title appears at position 0 while the cooking instruction lines are around position 23, giving a span of 23 which exceeds the threshold of 10, so the tiebreak would correctly keep only the earliest candidate. My implementation plan is to add the Polish cooking instruction regex, apply the distance-based tiebreak with a threshold of 10, and filter by word count using the criteria of 8 words with specific delimiters. Still writing the guard logic... I'm looking at the logic for handling multiple title candidates — when there are two or more ALL_CAPS headings, I join them with \"+\", but if there's only one ALL_CAPS title among mixed-case options, I collapse to the highest-scoring candidate instead of keeping all of them. The current code implicitly keeps everything when there are zero ALL_CAPS survivors, which I need to reconsider for the implementation.\n\nNow I'm defining a regex pattern to identify cooking instructions by checking if text starts with common cooking verbs like beat, fold, stir, mix, add, and so on.\n\nFor the Polish version, I'm creating a similar pattern that matches Polish cooking instruction verbs with OCR-resilient variations to handle common character substitutions, while excluding verbs that might appear in recipe titles. I'm defining a function that checks if text looks like a cooking instruction by examining word count and testing against regex patterns for both English and Polish cooking verbs. Then I'm adding a filter to reject lines with eight or more words unless they contain separator characters like plus signs, colons, or ampersands that indicate compound titles.\n\nI notice there's already a `words` variable being declared later in the function, so I should consolidate by moving the word-splitting logic to the top and reusing it throughout, rather than declaring it multiple times. Adding more filter checks...\n\nThe next checks handle pipe-separated headers, slash-separated navigation breadcrumbs (filtering only when there are 2+ slashes to preserve legitimate title/subtitle pairs), bullet-list markers that indicate ingredients or steps, known section labels, and finally a word-count validation that rejects single non-title words. Still writing filter checks... Testing the edge case with the merged title \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\" — it has 9 words but contains the \" & \" separator, so the exception allows it through the filter rather than rejecting it as body text.\n\nNow checking \"WHOLE WHEAT BREAD WITH SEEDS : SOURDOUGH VARIATION\" — this has 8 words and contains \" : \" as a separator, so it should also pass the filter exception. Looking at the test cases, I'm seeing that the multi-line title joins are all coming in under 8 words—the longest ones in the test suite are around 6 words each, so they're all within the safe range.\n\nFor the \"Pasta Carbonara + Tiramisu Classico\" case, I need to remember that the filtering happens on the individual candidates before they're joined together. So \"Pasta Carbonara\" and \"Tiramisu Classico\" each get evaluated separately as 2-word titles, which means they both pass the filter, and only then do they get combined with the \"+\" operator.\n\nI'm also double-checking the multi-line test where two titles appear deep in the text to make sure both get extracted and joined correctly.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":6551,"cache_read_input_tokens":47304,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":6551},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"