{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01B1hXd7SUJQVcGMYkqBbrBS","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→/**\n     2→ * Title Extraction\n     3→ * Extracts potential recipe title from OCR text using heuristics or semantic embeddings\n     4→ */\n     5→\n     6→import { cosineSimilarity } from \"./embeddings\";\n     7→\n     8→export type EmbedFn = (text: string) => Promise<Array<number>>;\n     9→\n    10→const TITLE_REFERENCE =\n    11→  \"recipe name, dish title, name of the food, nazwa przepisu, nazwa dania\";\n    12→const HEADER_REFERENCE =\n    13→  \"ingredients list, cooking directions, section heading, składniki, przygotowanie, sposób wykonania\";\n    14→const NOISE_REFERENCE =\n    15→  \"page number, table of contents, book footer, garbled text\";\n    16→\n    17→/**\n    18→ * Measurement units commonly found in ingredient lists\n    19→ */\n    20→const MEASUREMENT_PATTERNS = [\n    21→  // English\n    22→  \"cup\",\n    23→  \"cups\",\n    24→  \"tbsp\",\n    25→  \"tsp\",\n    26→  \"tablespoon\",\n    27→  \"teaspoon\",\n    28→  // \"oz\" and \"lb\" are matched with word boundaries in looksLikeIngredient\n    29→  // to avoid false positives (\"oz\" in \"mozzarella\", \"lb\" in \"albacore\")\n    30→  \"gram\",\n    31→  \"grams\",\n    32→  \"kg\",\n    33→  \"ml\",\n    34→  \"liter\",\n    35→  \"pinch\",\n    36→  \"dash\",\n    37→  \"handful\",\n    38→  // Polish\n    39→  \"łyżka\", \"łyżki\", \"łyżek\",           // tablespoon(s)\n    40→  \"łyżeczka\", \"łyżeczki\", \"łyżeczek\",   // teaspoon(s)\n    41→  \"szklanka\", \"szklanki\", \"szklanek\",    // cup(s)\n    42→  \"szczypta\",                            // pinch\n    43→  \"garść\",                               // handful\n    44→  \"opakowanie\", \"opakowania\",            // package(s)\n    45→  \"plasterek\", \"plasterki\",             // slice(s)\n    46→];\n    47→\n    48→/**\n    49→ * Patterns that identify recipe metadata lines (not titles)\n    50→ */\n    51→const METADATA_PATTERNS = [\n    52→  /^(SERVES?|MAKES?|YIELDS?)\\b/i,\n    53→  /^(PREP(ARATION)?|COOK(ING)?|PROOF|RISING|FERMENTATION|REST(ING)?)\\s*(AND\\s*)?(COOK(ING)?)?\\s*TIME/i,\n    54→  /^SAMPLE\\s+SCHEDULE\\b/i,\n    55→  /^BULK\\s+FERMENTATION\\b/i,\n    56→  /^(THIS\\s+RECIPE\\s+)?MAKES\\b/i,\n    57→  // Polish serving-size patterns: \"NA 3 PAPRYKI\", \"NA OKOŁO 1 KG\", \"DLA 4 OSÓB\"\n    58→  /^NA\\s+(\\d|OKOŁO)\\b/i,\n    59→  /^DLA\\s+\\d/i,\n    60→  // OCR-resilient: \"DLA\" + any token + serving-unit word (handles DLA & OSOB, DLA § OSOB, etc.)\n    61→  /^DLA\\s+\\S+\\s+OSOB/i,\n    62→  // OCR-resilient: \"DLA\" + single non-alphanumeric char (common digit→symbol OCR error)\n    63→  /^DLA\\s+[^a-zA-Z0-9\\s]\\s/i,\n    64→  // Time-unit metadata: any line containing \"N MIN\" or \"N GODZ\" is prep/cook/rest time,\n    65→  // regardless of OCR-corrupted prefix (catches PRZYGOTOWANTE, GOTOMANTE, etc.)\n    66→  /\\b\\d+\\s*MIN\\b/i,\n    67→  /\\b\\d+\\s*GODZ/i,\n    68→  // Season/category indicators\n    69→  /^SEZON\\s*:/i,\n    70→  /^KATEGORIA\\s*:/i,\n    71→  /^RODZAJ\\s*:/i,\n    72→];\n    73→\n    74→/**\n    75→ * Single-word non-title words — standalone OCR fragments unlikely to be recipe titles\n    76→ */\n    77→const NON_TITLE_WORDS = new Set([\n    78→  \"the\", \"and\", \"for\", \"but\", \"not\", \"you\", \"all\", \"can\", \"are\", \"was\",\n    79→  \"has\", \"his\", \"her\", \"its\", \"our\", \"who\", \"how\", \"may\", \"new\", \"now\",\n    80→  \"old\", \"see\", \"way\", \"did\", \"get\", \"let\", \"say\", \"she\", \"too\", \"use\",\n    81→  \"buns\", \"with\",\n    82→]);\n    83→\n    84→function looksLikeIngredient(line: string): boolean {\n    85→  const lowerLine = line.toLowerCase();\n    86→  if (MEASUREMENT_PATTERNS.some((pattern) => lowerLine.includes(pattern))) return true;\n    87→  // Compact metric: \"100g\", \"50ml\", \"250g\" — digit immediately followed by g/ml/kg\n    88→  if (/\\b\\d+\\s*(?:g|ml|kg)\\b/i.test(line)) return true;\n    89→  // \"to taste\" / \"do smaku\" — qualitative ingredient with no unit\n    90→  if (/\\bto taste\\b/i.test(line) || /\\bdo smaku\\b/i.test(line)) return true;\n    91→  return false;\n    92→}\n    93→\n    94→function startsWithNumber(line: string): boolean {\n    95→  // Match lines starting with a digit, or bullet-then-digit (e.g., \"- 2 jajka\")\n    96→  return /^\\s*(?:[-•*]\\s*)?\\d/.test(line);\n    97→}\n    98→\n    99→function stripDiacritics(text: string): string {\n   100→  return text.normalize(\"NFKD\").replace(/[\\u0300-\\u036f]/g, \"\");\n   101→}\n   102→\n   103→/**\n   104→ * Known recipe section labels — these are structural headers, not recipe titles.\n   105→ * Matched case-insensitively after trimming, stripping trailing punctuation, and stripping diacritics.\n   106→ * Polish entries are stored without diacritics for OCR resilience (e.g. \"SKLADNIKI\" matches \"składniki\").\n   107→ */\n   108→const SECTION_LABELS = new Set([\n   109→  // English\n   110→  \"ingredients\", \"directions\", \"instructions\", \"method\", \"preparation\",\n   111→  \"steps\", \"notes\", \"tip\", \"tips\", \"variations\", \"variation\",\n   112→  \"garnish\", \"topping\", \"toppings\", \"frosting\", \"filling\",\n   113→  // Polish — recipe section labels (stored without diacritics for OCR resilience)\n   114→  \"skladniki\", \"przygotowanie\", \"sposob przygotowania\", \"sposob wykonania\",\n   115→  \"wykonanie\", \"wskazowki\", \"podpowiedz\", \"warianty\",\n   116→  \"sos\", \"nadzienie\", \"polewa\", \"lukier\", \"ciasto\",  // ciasto = dough/pastry base (recipe-internal section AND chapter label)\n   117→  // Polish — recipe-book chapter/category labels (food groups, meal types)\n   118→  \"warzywa\",          // vegetables\n   119→  \"mieso\",            // meat (mięso)\n   120→  \"miesa\",            // meats (mięsa)\n   121→  \"ryby\",             // fish\n   122→  \"owoce morza\",      // seafood\n   123→  \"zupy\",             // soups\n   124→  \"salatki\",          // salads (sałatki)\n   125→  \"desery\",           // desserts\n   126→  \"napoje\",           // drinks\n   127→  \"pieczywo\",         // bread/baked goods\n   128→  \"przekaski\",        // appetizers/snacks\n   129→  \"sniadania\",        // breakfasts (śniadania)\n   130→  \"obiady\",           // dinners/lunches\n   131→  \"kolacje\",          // suppers\n   132→  \"makarony\",         // pasta dishes\n   133→  \"kasza\",            // groats/grains\n   134→  \"kasze\",            // groats/grains (plural)\n   135→  \"dania glowne\",     // main courses (dania główne)\n   136→  \"przystawki\",       // starters\n   137→  \"dodatki\",          // side dishes\n   138→  \"przetwory\",        // preserves\n   139→  \"wypieki\",          // baked goods\n   140→  \"ciasta\",           // cakes (plural)\n   141→  \"ciastka\",          // cookies\n   142→  \"torty\",            // layer cakes\n   143→  \"placki\",           // pancakes/flatbreads\n   144→  \"koktajle\",         // cocktails/smoothies\n   145→]);\n   146→\n   147→function isSectionLabel(text: string): boolean {\n   148→  const normalized = stripDiacritics(text.trim().replace(/[:.]$/, \"\").toLowerCase());\n   149→  return SECTION_LABELS.has(normalized);\n   150→}\n   151→\n   152→/**\n   153→ * Recipe-internal section labels that should ALWAYS block multi-line joins,\n   154→ * even when the combined word count is ≥ 3.\n   155→ * Category labels (\"zupy\", \"placki\", etc.) are NOT in this set — they can\n   156→ * legitimately start a multi-word recipe title like \"Zupy Zimowe Warzywne\".\n   157→ */\n   158→const ALWAYS_BLOCK_JOIN_LABELS = new Set([\n   159→  \"ingredients\", \"directions\", \"instructions\", \"method\", \"preparation\",\n   160→  \"steps\", \"notes\", \"tip\", \"tips\", \"variations\", \"variation\",\n   161→  \"garnish\", \"topping\", \"toppings\", \"frosting\", \"filling\",\n   162→  \"skladniki\", \"przygotowanie\", \"sposob przygotowania\", \"sposob wykonania\",\n   163→  \"wykonanie\", \"wskazowki\", \"podpowiedz\", \"warianty\",\n   164→  \"sos\", \"nadzienie\", \"polewa\", \"lukier\", \"ciasto\",\n   165→]);\n   166→\n   167→function isAlwaysBlockJoinLabel(text: string): boolean {\n   168→  const normalized = stripDiacritics(text.trim().replace(/[:.]$/, \"\").toLowerCase());\n   169→  return ALWAYS_BLOCK_JOIN_LABELS.has(normalized);\n   170→}\n   171→\n   172→function isAllCaps(line: string): boolean {\n   173→  const letters = line.replace(/[^a-zA-Z]/g, \"\");\n   174→  return letters.length > 0 && letters === letters.toUpperCase();\n   175→}\n   176→\n   177→function looksLikeMetadata(text: string): boolean {\n   178→  return METADATA_PATTERNS.some((pattern) => pattern.test(text.trim()));\n   179→}\n   180→\n   181→function isLikelyGarbled(text: string): boolean {\n   182→  const letters = text.replace(/[^a-zA-Z]/g, \"\");\n   183→  if (letters.length < 2) return true;\n   184→\n   185→  // Check vowel ratio — English/Polish text typically has 30–50% vowels\n   186→  const vowels = letters.replace(/[^aeiouAEIOUyYąęóĄĘÓ]/g, \"\").length;\n   187→  const vowelRatio = vowels / letters.length;\n   188→  if (vowelRatio < 0.15 || vowelRatio > 0.85) return true;\n   189→\n   190→  // Single orphaned word ≤3 letters that isn't a common word\n   191→  const words = text.trim().split(/\\s+/);\n   192→  const COMMON_SHORT = new Set([\n   193→    \"the\", \"and\", \"for\", \"but\", \"not\", \"you\", \"all\", \"can\", \"had\", \"her\",\n   194→    \"was\", \"one\", \"our\", \"out\", \"are\", \"has\", \"his\", \"how\", \"its\", \"may\",\n   195→    \"new\", \"now\", \"old\", \"see\", \"way\", \"who\", \"did\", \"get\", \"let\", \"say\",\n   196→    \"she\", \"too\", \"use\",\n   197→  ]);\n   198→  // Count all Unicode letters (not just ASCII) so Polish words like \"Żur\" (3 letters) pass\n   199→  const unicodeLetters = text.trim().replace(/[^a-zA-ZąćęłńóśźżĄĆĘŁŃÓŚŹŻ]/g, \"\");\n   200→  if (words.length === 1 && unicodeLetters.length <= 3 && !COMMON_SHORT.has(text.trim().toLowerCase())) {\n   201→    return true;\n   202→  }\n   203→\n   204→  // Single word with internal lowercase→uppercase transition — OCR noise (e.g., \"UuIw\", \"aBC\")\n   205→  // No recipe title uses this pattern as a standalone single-word candidate.\n   206→  if (words.length === 1 && /[a-z][A-Z]/.test(text.trim())) {\n   207→    return true;\n   208→  }\n   209→\n   210→  // Recipe titles never start with a lowercase letter\n   211→  if (/^[a-z]/.test(text.trim())) {\n   212→    return true;\n   213→  }\n   214→\n   215→  // Mid-text sentence boundary (\". \" followed by a letter) — body text fragment spliced from multiple sentences\n   216→  const trimmed = text.trim();\n   217→  if (/\\.\\s+[a-zA-Z]/.test(trimmed) && !trimmed.endsWith(\")\")) {\n   218→    return true;\n   219→  }\n   220→\n   221→  // Multi-word candidate containing a garbled OCR fragment: a short lowercase word that isn't a known short word\n   222→  if (words.length >= 2) {\n   223→    const commonShort2 = new Set([\n   224→      \"a\", \"i\", \"of\", \"or\", \"to\", \"in\", \"on\", \"is\", \"it\", \"an\",\n   225→      \"as\", \"at\", \"by\", \"do\", \"go\", \"if\", \"no\", \"so\", \"up\", \"we\",\n   226→      \"w\", \"z\",   // Polish prepositions (basic)\n   227→      \"ze\", \"bo\", \"na\", \"ni\", \"po\", \"ku\", \"od\", \"za\", \"co\",  // Polish prepositions (extended)\n   228→    ]);\n   229→    const hasGarbledWord = words.some(\n   230→      (w) =>\n   231→        /^[a-z]/.test(w) &&\n   232→        w.replace(/[^a-z]/g, \"\").length <= 2 &&\n   233→        !commonShort2.has(w.toLowerCase())\n   234→    );\n   235→    if (hasGarbledWord) {\n   236→      return true;\n   237→    }\n   238→  }\n   239→\n   240→  return false;\n   241→}\n   242→\n   243→const COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS = /^(beat|fold|stir|mix|add|pour|bake|cook|cool|remove|place|combine|whisk|knead|roll|spread|brush|slice|chop|dice|mince|drain|rinse|peel|grate|melt|simmer|boil|fry|sauté|saute|roast|grill|broil|steam|let|set|transfer|serve|garnish|arrange|sprinkle|season|preheat|cover|uncover|reduce|bring|toss|cut|trim|shape|form)\\b/i;\n   244→\n   245→// Polish imperative cooking verbs (with OCR-resilient forms — no diacritics required).\n   246→// These cover the most common recipe instruction starters. Includes common OCR-corrupted\n   247→// forms (e.g., \"Smaż\" → \"Smaz\", \"Dodaj\" → \"Dodaj\").\n   248→// Note: only verbs that NEVER start a recipe title. \"Piecz\" (bake) is excluded because\n   249→// \"Pieczeń\" (roast) and \"Pieczarki\" (mushrooms) share the prefix.\n   250→const POLISH_COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS = /^(podawaj|dodaj|dodawaj|sma[zż]|gotuj|odced[zź]|wymiesza[jJ]|miesza[jJ]|wlej|nalej|przygotuj|zagotuj|pokr[oó]j|obierz|wrzuc|wrzuć|usma[zż]|podsma[zż]|prze[lł][oó][zż]|zblenduj|ubij|roztrzepaj|rozprowad[zź]|wyrob|zamieszaj|posyp|polej|odstaw|na[lł][oó][zż]|przykryj|odkryj|wstaw|zdejmij|ods[aą]cz|rozgrzej|posiekaj|zetrzyj|wy[lł][oó][zż]|wyjmij|ukr[oó]j|przekr[oó]j|formuj|ugniataj|rozwałkuj)\\b/i;\n   251→\n   252→function looksLikeCookingInstruction(text: string): boolean {\n   253→  const words = text.trim().split(/\\s+/);\n   254→  if (words.length < 4) return false;  // Instructions are multi-word sentences\n   255→  if (COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS.test(text.trim())) return true;\n   256→  if (POLISH_COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS.test(text.trim())) return true;\n   257→  return false;\n   258→}\n   259→\n   260→function passesHardFilters(text: string): boolean {\n   261→  if (text.length < 3 || text.length > 80) return false;\n   262→  if (looksLikeIngredient(text)) return false;\n   263→  if (startsWithNumber(text)) return false;\n   264→  if (looksLikeMetadata(text)) return false;\n   265→  if (isLikelyGarbled(text)) return false;\n   266→  if (looksLikeCookingInstruction(text)) return false;\n   267→  // Pipe-separated lines are book category/chapter headers, not recipe titles\n   268→  if (text.includes(\" | \")) return false;\n   269→  // Slash-separated breadcrumbs (e.g., \"/ Jesien / Zupy\") are navigation, not titles\n   270→  // Only filter when 2+ slashes are present — single-slash lines like\n   271→  // \"TITLE / SUBTITLE\" are legitimate continuation-merged titles\n   272→  if ((text.match(/\\//g) || []).length >= 2) return false;\n   273→  // Bullet-list items (ingredients or instruction steps) are never titles\n   274→  if (/^\\s*[-•*]\\s/.test(text)) return false;\n   275→  // Known recipe section labels are structural headers, not titles\n   276→  if (isSectionLabel(text)) return false;\n   277→  // Single-word non-title fragments\n   278→  const words = text.trim().split(/\\s+/);\n   279→  if (words.length === 1 && NON_TITLE_WORDS.has(text.trim().toLowerCase())) return false;\n   280→  // Lines with ≥8 words are almost certainly body text, not titles.\n   281→  // Exception: multi-title compounds with \" + \", \" : \", or \" & \" separators are allowed.\n   282→  if (words.length >= 8 && !/ [+:&] /.test(text)) return false;\n   283→  return true;\n   284→}\n   285→\n   286→/**\n   287→ * Detect initial burst of short garbled lines.\n   288→ * Returns the index of the first non-garbled or long line.\n   289→ */\n   290→function findBurstEnd(lines: Array<{ text: string }>): number {\n   291→  let i = 0;\n   292→  while (i < lines.length && lines[i].text.length < 20 && isLikelyGarbled(lines[i].text)) {\n   293→    i++;\n   294→  }\n   295→  // Skip long instruction-like prologues: if 5+ consecutive lines look like cooking instructions,\n   296→  // skip them to find the actual title region.\n   297→  if (i === 0) {\n   298→    let j = 0;\n   299→    while (j < lines.length && looksLikeCookingInstruction(lines[j].text)) {\n   300→      j++;\n   301→    }\n   302→    if (j >= 5) {\n   303→      i = j;\n   304→    }\n   305→  }\n   306→  return i;\n   307→}\n   308→\n   309→function stripParentheticalGloss(text: string): string {\n   310→  // Strip trailing English-gloss parentheticals from ALL_CAPS titles.\n   311→  // e.g. \"PIEROGI RUSKIE (Boiled Dumplings with Potato and Cheese)\" → \"PIEROGI RUSKIE\"\n   312→  // Keep if parenthetical is ALL_CAPS (variation/subtitle in same language).\n   313→  // Keep if both base and paren are mixed-case (both are part of the title).\n   314→  const match = text.match(/^(.+?)\\s*\\(([^)]+)\\)\\s*$/);\n   315→  if (!match) return text;\n   316→  const [, base, paren] = match;\n   317→  if (isAllCaps(paren)) return text;\n   318→  if (!isAllCaps(base) && !isAllCaps(paren)) return text;\n   319→  return base.trim();\n   320→}\n   321→\n   322→function stripPageNumber(text: string): string {\n   323→  // \"34  Berry Jam\" → \"Berry Jam\" (2+ spaces distinguishes from \"2 eggs\")\n   324→  const match = text.match(/^\\d{1,3}\\s{2,}(.+)$/);\n   325→  return match ? match[1] : text;\n   326→}\n   327→\n   328→function wordCount(text: string): number {\n   329→  return text.split(/\\s+/).filter((w) => w.length > 0).length;\n   330→}\n   331→\n   332→/**\n   333→ * Build candidate strings from lines: single lines plus multi-line joins (2-3 consecutive).\n   334→ * Skips initial burst of short garbled lines. Scans all remaining lines. Caps at 25.\n   335→ */\n   336→export type CandidateOrigin = \"single\" | \"2-line\" | \"3-line\";\n   337→\n   338→function buildCandidates(\n   339→  lines: Array<string>\n   340→): Array<{ text: string; position: number; origin: CandidateOrigin }> {\n   341→  const nonEmptyLines: Array<{ text: string; index: number }> = [];\n   342→\n   343→  for (let i = 0; i < lines.length; i++) {\n   344→    const trimmed = lines[i].trim();\n   345→    if (trimmed.length > 0) {\n   346→      nonEmptyLines.push({ text: trimmed, index: i });\n   347→    }\n   348→  }\n   349→\n   350→  const burstEnd = findBurstEnd(nonEmptyLines);\n   351→\n   352→  // Pre-merge consecutive short ALL_CAPS lines (OCR-fragmented headings).\n   353→  // When a sequence of 2+ ALL_CAPS lines each has ≤2 words and ≤25 chars, they are\n   354→  // almost certainly OCR fragments of a single heading. Merge them into one line so\n   355→  // the complete title enters the candidate pool without hitting the 3-line join ceiling.\n   356→  const capsCoalesced: Array<{ text: string; index: number }> = [];\n   357→  let ci = burstEnd;\n   358→  while (ci < nonEmptyLines.length) {\n   359→    const line = nonEmptyLines[ci];\n   360→    if (\n   361→      isAllCaps(line.text) &&\n   362→      wordCount(line.text) <= 2 &&\n   363→      line.text.length <= 25 &&\n   364→      !isSectionLabel(line.text) &&\n   365→      !looksLikeMetadata(line.text)\n   366→    ) {\n   367→      let merged = line.text;\n   368→      const startIndex = line.index;\n   369→      let j = ci + 1;\n   370→      while (j < nonEmptyLines.length) {\n   371→        const next = nonEmptyLines[j];\n   372→        if (\n   373→          isAllCaps(next.text) &&\n   374→          wordCount(next.text) <= 2 &&\n   375→          next.text.length <= 25 &&\n   376→          !isSectionLabel(next.text) &&\n   377→          !looksLikeMetadata(next.text) &&\n   378→          (merged + \" \" + next.text).length <= 80\n   379→        ) {\n   380→          merged += \" \" + next.text;\n   381→          j++;\n   382→        } else {\n   383→          break;\n   384→        }\n   385→      }\n   386→      if (j > ci + 1) {\n   387→        capsCoalesced.push({ text: merged, index: startIndex });\n   388→        ci = j;\n   389→        continue;\n   390→      }\n   391→    }\n   392→    capsCoalesced.push(line);\n   393→    ci++;\n   394→  }\n   395→\n   396→  // Pre-merge continuation lines: a line starting with /&+:( is never a standalone title.\n   397→  // Merge it into the preceding line so the complete title enters the pool as a single candidate,\n   398→  // avoiding the fragile chain of conditions required by the downstream join survival logic.\n   399→  // Limitation: only one continuation line per preceding line is merged. Titles split across\n   400→  // three or more lines with continuation tokens (rare in practice) are not handled here —\n   401→  // the downstream 2-line and 3-line join candidates cover those cases instead.\n   402→  const mergedLines: Array<{ text: string; index: number }> = [];\n   403→  for (let i = 0; i < capsCoalesced.length; i++) {\n   404→    const line = capsCoalesced[i];\n   405→    if (i + 1 < capsCoalesced.length) {\n   406→      const nextText = capsCoalesced[i + 1].text;\n   407→      if (/^[/&+:(]/.test(nextText)) {\n   408→        mergedLines.push({ text: `${line.text} ${nextText}`, index: line.index });\n   409→        i++;\n   410→        continue;\n   411→      }\n   412→    }\n   413→    mergedLines.push(line);\n   414→  }\n   415→\n   416→  const candidates: Array<{ text: string; position: number; origin: CandidateOrigin }> = [];\n   417→  const seen = new Set<string>();\n   418→\n   419→  // Build a set of positions to skip: short ALL_CAPS lines immediately following metadata\n   420→  const metadataContinuationPositions = new Set<number>();\n   421→  for (let i = 0; i < mergedLines.length - 1; i++) {\n   422→    if (looksLikeMetadata(mergedLines[i].text)) {\n   423→      const next = mergedLines[i + 1];\n   424→      if (isAllCaps(next.text) && wordCount(next.text) <= 2 && next.text.length <= 15) {\n   425→        metadataContinuationPositions.add(next.index);\n   426→      }\n   427→    }\n   428→  }\n   429→\n   430→  for (let i = 0; i < mergedLines.length; i++) {\n   431→    const line = mergedLines[i];\n   432→\n   433→    // Skip metadata continuation fragments\n   434→    if (metadataContinuationPositions.has(line.index)) continue;\n   435→\n   436→    // Single line — strip page-number prefixes and parenthetical glosses before scoring\n   437→    const singleText = stripParentheticalGloss(stripPageNumber(line.text));\n   438→    if (passesHardFilters(singleText)) {\n   439→      const norm = singleText.toLowerCase();\n   440→      if (!seen.has(norm)) {\n   441→        seen.add(norm);\n   442→        candidates.push({ text: singleText, position: line.index, origin: \"single\" });\n   443→      }\n   444→    }\n   445→\n   446→    // 2-line join — skip if first line is a section label AND join would be ≤2 words\n   447→    // (a section label followed by modifiers is likely a recipe title, not a category header)\n   448→    if (i + 1 < mergedLines.length) {\n   449→      const joined2 = `${line.text} ${mergedLines[i + 1].text}`;\n   450→      const shouldBlock2 = isSectionLabel(line.text) &&\n   451→        (wordCount(joined2) <= 2 || isAlwaysBlockJoinLabel(line.text));\n   452→      if (!shouldBlock2 && passesHardFilters(joined2)) {\n   453→        const norm = joined2.toLowerCase();\n   454→        if (!seen.has(norm)) {\n   455→          seen.add(norm);\n   456→          candidates.push({ text: joined2, position: line.index, origin: \"2-line\" });\n   457→        }\n   458→      }\n   459→    }\n   460→\n   461→    // 3-line join — skip if first line is a section label AND join would be ≤2 words\n   462→    if (i + 2 < mergedLines.length) {\n   463→      const joined3 = `${line.text} ${mergedLines[i + 1].text} ${mergedLines[i + 2].text}`;\n   464→      const shouldBlock3 = isSectionLabel(line.text) &&\n   465→        (wordCount(joined3) <= 2 || isAlwaysBlockJoinLabel(line.text));\n   466→      if (!shouldBlock3 && passesHardFilters(joined3)) {\n   467→        const norm = joined3.toLowerCase();\n   468→        if (!seen.has(norm)) {\n   469→          seen.add(norm);\n   470→          candidates.push({ text: joined3, position: line.index, origin: \"3-line\" });\n   471→        }\n   472→      }\n   473→    }\n   474→  }\n   475→\n   476→  // Pre-filter to 25 before embedding calls: prefer ALL_CAPS and short candidates.\n   477→  // Position-based scoring handles final ranking.\n   478→  if (candidates.length > 25) {\n   479→    const prioritized = candidates.slice().sort((a, b) => {\n   480→      const aAllCaps = isAllCaps(a.text) ? 0 : 1;\n   481→      const bAllCaps = isAllCaps(b.text) ? 0 : 1;\n   482→      if (aAllCaps !== bAllCaps) return aAllCaps - bAllCaps;\n   483→      const aShort = wordCount(a.text) <= 5 ? 0 : 1;\n   484→      const bShort = wordCount(b.text) <= 5 ? 0 : 1;\n   485→      return aShort - bShort;\n   486→    });\n   487→    return prioritized.slice(0, 25);\n   488→  }\n   489→\n   490→  return candidates;\n   491→}\n   492→\n   493→// Module-level cache for reference embeddings\n   494→let cachedTitleRefEmbedding: Array<number> | null = null;\n   495→let cachedHeaderRefEmbedding: Array<number> | null = null;\n   496→let cachedNoiseRefEmbedding: Array<number> | null = null;\n   497→\n   498→export function _resetEmbeddingCacheForTests(): void {\n   499→  cachedTitleRefEmbedding = null;\n   500→  cachedHeaderRefEmbedding = null;\n   501→  cachedNoiseRefEmbedding = null;\n   502→}\n   503→\n   504→export async function extractTitleWithEmbeddings(\n   505→  text: string,\n   506→  embed: EmbedFn\n   507→): Promise<string | undefined> {\n   508→  if (!text || text.trim().length === 0) {\n   509→    return undefined;\n   510→  }\n   511→\n   512→  const lines = text.split(\"\\n\");\n   513→  const candidates = buildCandidates(lines);\n   514→\n   515→  if (candidates.length === 0) {\n   516→    return undefined;\n   517→  }\n   518→\n   519→  // Cache reference embeddings\n   520→  if (!cachedTitleRefEmbedding) {\n   521→    cachedTitleRefEmbedding = await embed(TITLE_REFERENCE);\n   522→  }\n   523→  if (!cachedHeaderRefEmbedding) {\n   524→    cachedHeaderRefEmbedding = await embed(HEADER_REFERENCE);\n   525→  }\n   526→  if (!cachedNoiseRefEmbedding) {\n   527→    cachedNoiseRefEmbedding = await embed(NOISE_REFERENCE);\n   528→  }\n   529→\n   530→  // Find ALL_CAPS candidates with ≥2 words where every significant word has ≥4 alpha letters.\n   531→  // Insignificant tokens (≤1 alpha letter: \"/\", \"&\", \"+\", \":\", \"D)\", etc.) are filtered before\n   532→  // the check so that multi-line joins with continuation punctuation still qualify.\n   533→  const isStructuralHeading = (c: { text: string }): boolean => {\n   534→    if (!isAllCaps(c.text) || wordCount(c.text) < 2) return false;\n   535→    const sigWords = c.text.trim().split(/\\s+/).filter((w) => w.replace(/[^A-Z]/g, \"\").length > 1);\n   536→    return sigWords.length >= 2 && sigWords.every((w) => w.replace(/[^A-Z]/g, \"\").length >= 4);\n   537→  };\n   538→\n   539→  // Pass 1: compute rawScore for all candidates (embedding quality signal)\n   540→  const rawScored: Array<{ text: string; position: number; origin: CandidateOrigin; rawScore: number; embedding: Array<number> }> = [];\n   541→  for (const candidate of candidates) {\n   542→    const embedding = await embed(candidate.text);\n   543→    const titleSim = cosineSimilarity(embedding, cachedTitleRefEmbedding);\n   544→    const headerSim = cosineSimilarity(embedding, cachedHeaderRefEmbedding);\n   545→    const noiseSim = cosineSimilarity(embedding, cachedNoiseRefEmbedding);\n   546→    const rawScore = titleSim - Math.max(headerSim, noiseSim);\n   547→    rawScored.push({ text: candidate.text, position: candidate.position, origin: candidate.origin, rawScore, embedding });\n   548→  }\n   549→\n   550→  // Select baseHeading by embedding quality (rawScore), not position.\n   551→  // This prevents OCR-garbled fragments from claiming the structural heading slot.\n   552→  const structuralCandidates = rawScored.filter((s) => isStructuralHeading(s));\n   553→\n   554→  // Penalize structural headings with truncated OCR words:\n   555→  // if \"FRON\" appears and another heading has \"SAFFRON\", \"FRON\" is likely garbled.\n   556→  for (const sc of structuralCandidates) {\n   557→    const sigWords = sc.text.split(/\\s+/).filter((w) => w.replace(/[^A-Z]/g, \"\").length >= 4);\n   558→    for (const other of structuralCandidates) {\n   559→      if (other === sc) continue;\n   560→      const otherSigWords = other.text.split(/\\s+/).filter((w) => w.replace(/[^A-Z]/g, \"\").length >= 4);\n   561→      const hasTruncation = sigWords.some((w) =>\n   562→        otherSigWords.some((ow) => ow !== w && ow.length > w.length && ow.endsWith(w))\n   563→      );\n   564→      if (hasTruncation) {\n   565→        sc.rawScore = -1.0;  // Hard disqualification — truncated OCR artifact\n   566→        break;\n   567→      }\n   568→    }\n   569→  }\n   570→\n   571→  const bestStructural = structuralCandidates.length > 0\n   572→    ? structuralCandidates.reduce((a, b) => {\n   573→        const scoreDiff = a.rawScore - b.rawScore;\n   574→        if (Math.abs(scoreDiff) > 0.03) return scoreDiff > 0 ? a : b;\n   575→        // Tiebreak: single-line origin beats multi-line joins (avoids conflating two separate headings)\n   576→        if (a.origin === \"single\" && b.origin !== \"single\") return a;\n   577→        if (b.origin === \"single\" && a.origin !== \"single\") return b;\n   578→        // Tiebreak: more words (more specific) → better\n   579→        const wcDiff = wordCount(b.text) - wordCount(a.text);\n   580→        if (wcDiff !== 0) return wcDiff > 0 ? b : a;\n   581→        // Tiebreak: earlier position → better\n   582→        return a.position < b.position ? a : b;\n   583→      })\n   584→    : null;\n   585→  const baseHeading = bestStructural ?? undefined;\n   586→\n   587→  // When the best structural heading has a continuation on the next line introduced by a\n   588→  // punctuation token (/, &, +, :, or parenthesis), prefer the longer 2-line join as the\n   589→  // complete heading. E.g. \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK\" + \"/ COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)\".\n   590→  // Guard: the remainder after the prefix must start with a continuation character to avoid\n   591→  // merging two separate consecutive recipe titles (FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS stays separate\n   592→  // from FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS because \"FINNISH\" does not start with a continuation token).\n   593→  let firstStructuralHeading = baseHeading && (\n   594→    rawScored.find((c) => {\n   595→      if (!isStructuralHeading(c)) return false;\n   596→      const hLower = baseHeading.text.toLowerCase();\n   597→      const cLower = c.text.toLowerCase();\n   598→      return cLower.startsWith(hLower + \" \") && /^[/&+:(]/.test(cLower.slice(hLower.length + 1));\n   599→    }) ?? baseHeading\n   600→  );\n   601→\n   602→  // Pass 2: apply bonuses\n   603→  const scored: Array<{ text: string; position: number; origin: CandidateOrigin; score: number; rawScore: number; baseScore: number; thresholdScore: number }> = rawScored.map((rs) => {\n   604→    // Position factor: multiplicative tiebreaker — amplifies existing signal, doesn't replace it\n   605→    const relativePosition = rs.position / lines.length;\n   606→    const positionFactor = relativePosition < 0.5\n   607→      ? 1.0 + 0.12 * (1 - relativePosition * 2)\n   608→      : 1.0;\n   609→\n   610→    // ALL_CAPS bonus: recipe books use ALL_CAPS for titles and section headings.\n   611→    // Single-word ALL_CAPS terms are overwhelmingly section/category labels, not recipe titles;\n   612→    // real recipe titles in ALL_CAPS are almost always multi-word. Reduce the bonus for single words.\n   613→    const allCapsBonus = isAllCaps(rs.text) && rs.text.replace(/[^a-zA-Z]/g, \"\").length >= 4\n   614→      ? (wordCount(rs.text) >= 2 ? 0.08 : 0.03)\n   615→      : 0;\n   616→\n   617→    // Structural heading bonus: best ALL_CAPS heading (or its continuation join) is almost always the recipe title\n   618→    const structuralBonus = firstStructuralHeading && rs.text === firstStructuralHeading.text ? 0.10 : 0;\n   619→\n   620→    // thresholdScore excludes structural bonus so the bonus doesn't inflate the threshold\n   621→    // and prevent equally-valid structural headings from passing on multi-recipe pages.\n   622→    const thresholdScore = rs.rawScore + allCapsBonus;\n   623→    // baseScore excludes position factor — used for diagnostics and ranking\n   624→    const baseScore = rs.rawScore + allCapsBonus + structuralBonus;\n   625→    const score = rs.rawScore * positionFactor + allCapsBonus + structuralBonus;\n   626→    return { text: rs.text, position: rs.position, origin: rs.origin, score, rawScore: rs.rawScore, baseScore, thresholdScore };\n   627→  });\n   628→\n   629→  if (scored.length === 0) {\n   630→    return undefined;\n   631→  }\n   632→\n   633→  // --- Pre-threshold bilingual title detection ---\n   634→  // When a mixed-case candidate at position 0 is followed by an ALL_CAPS candidate\n   635→  // at position ≤ 2 that is semantically similar to it, this is a bilingual recipe\n   636→  // page (e.g., Polish title + ALL_CAPS Korean romanization). Suppress confirmed\n   637→  // translation candidates before computing threshold so their bonuses don't inflate\n   638→  // the threshold beyond the mixed-case title's reach.\n   639→  // Note: we check position ≤ 2 (local proximity), not global ALL_CAPS count, so\n   640→  // section headers later in the document (SKŁADNIKI, WARZYWA, etc.) are irrelevant.\n   641→  let translationCandidates: typeof scored = [];\n   642→  let scoredForThreshold = scored;\n   643→  const prePos0 = scored.find((s) => s.position === 0 && !isAllCaps(s.text));\n   644→  if (prePos0) {\n   645→    const nearbyAllCaps = scored.filter(\n   646→      (s) => isAllCaps(s.text) && s.position >= 1 && s.position <= 2 && s.origin === \"single\"\n   647→    );\n   648→    const pos0Embedding = rawScored.find((r) => r.text === prePos0.text)?.embedding;\n   649→\n   650→    // Method 1: embedding similarity (works for related languages)\n   651→    if (pos0Embedding && nearbyAllCaps.length > 0) {\n   652→      translationCandidates = nearbyAllCaps.filter((cap) => {\n   653→        const capEmbedding = rawScored.find((r) => r.text === cap.text)?.embedding;\n   654→        if (!capEmbedding) return false;\n   655→        return cosineSimilarity(pos0Embedding, capEmbedding) > 0.4;\n   656→      });\n   657→    }\n   658→\n   659→    // Method 2: layout-based detection (cross-lingual fallback).\n   660→    // When embedding similarity is insufficient (e.g. Polish ↔ Korean romanization),\n   661→    // detect bilingual layout by position and word overlap:\n   662→    // mixed-case ≥2 words at pos 0 + ALL_CAPS ≥2 words at pos 1-2 with no shared words.\n   663→    if (translationCandidates.length === 0 && wordCount(prePos0.text) >= 2) {\n   664→      const pos0Words = new Set(\n   665→        prePos0.text.toLowerCase().split(/\\s+/).filter((w) => w.length > 2)\n   666→      );\n   667→      translationCandidates = nearbyAllCaps.filter((cap) => {\n   668→        if (wordCount(cap.text) < 2) return false;\n   669→        const capWords = cap.text.toLowerCase().split(/\\s+/).filter((w) => w.length > 2);\n   670→        return !capWords.some((w) => pos0Words.has(w));\n   671→      });\n   672→    }\n   673→\n   674→    if (translationCandidates.length > 0) {\n   675→      // Suppress standalone translations and any multi-line joins that embed the translation\n   676→      // as a suffix or substring (e.g. \"Smażona zielona fasolka GREEN BEANS BORKEUM\" ends with\n   677→      // the translation; \"Title GREEN BEANS BORKEUM 그린빈\" includes it as a substring).\n   678→      scoredForThreshold = scored.filter((s) => {\n   679→        const sLower = s.text.toLowerCase();\n   680→        return !translationCandidates.some((t) => {\n   681→          const tLower = t.text.toLowerCase();\n   682→          return sLower.startsWith(tLower) ||\n   683→                 sLower.endsWith(\" \" + tLower) ||\n   684→                 sLower.includes(\" \" + tLower);\n   685→        });\n   686→      });\n   687→    }\n   688→  }\n   689→\n   690→  // Fix 2: If the structural heading was identified as a bilingual translation, reassign it.\n   691→  // This prevents the translation's ALL_CAPS bonus from inflating the threshold and ensures\n   692→  // the fallback path in scored also uses the correct heading.\n   693→  if (\n   694→    translationCandidates.length > 0 &&\n   695→    firstStructuralHeading &&\n   696→    translationCandidates.some((t) => t.text === firstStructuralHeading!.text)\n   697→  ) {\n   698→    const nonTranslationStructural = structuralCandidates.filter(\n   699→      (sc) => !translationCandidates.some((t) => t.text === sc.text)\n   700→    );\n   701→    const newHeading = nonTranslationStructural.length > 0\n   702→      ? nonTranslationStructural.reduce((a, b) => a.rawScore > b.rawScore ? a : b)\n   703→      : undefined;\n   704→\n   705→    // Patch scored array: remove old structural bonus, apply new one\n   706→    for (const s of scored) {\n   707→      if (s.text === firstStructuralHeading.text) {\n   708→        s.score -= 0.10;\n   709→        s.baseScore -= 0.10;\n   710→      }\n   711→      if (newHeading && s.text === newHeading.text) {\n   712→        s.score += 0.10;\n   713→        s.baseScore += 0.10;\n   714→      }\n   715→    }\n   716→    // Update reference for downstream prefix-removal logic\n   717→    firstStructuralHeading = newHeading ?? undefined;\n   718→  }\n   719→\n   720→  // Use thresholdScore (excludes structural bonus) so the structural bonus doesn't inflate\n   721→  // the threshold and block equally-valid headings on multi-recipe pages.\n   722→  const bestThresholdScore = Math.max(...scoredForThreshold.map((s) => s.thresholdScore));\n   723→  const threshold = Math.max(0.08, bestThresholdScore * 0.7);\n   724→\n   725→  // Filter candidates above threshold\n   726→  let selected = scoredForThreshold.filter((s) => s.score >= threshold);\n   727→\n   728→  // Empty-pool fallback: when threshold filtering discards every candidate,\n   729→  // the hard filters' structural verdict should not be overruled by weak\n   730→  // embedding differentiation. Return the best positional candidate.\n   731→  if (selected.length === 0 && scored.length > 0) {\n   732→    const fallback = scored\n   733→      .slice()\n   734→      .sort((a, b) => a.position - b.position || b.score - a.score);\n   735→    selected = [fallback[0]];\n   736→  }\n   737→\n   738→  // Remove word-boundary prefixes of firstStructuralHeading when the heading itself survived\n   739→  // the threshold. Cases:\n   740→  //   ARAYES case:  firstStructuralHeading = \"ARAYES SHRAK\" (2-word join qualifies; \"ARAYES\"\n   741→  //     alone = 1 word, so it never qualified). Filter removes \"ARAYES\" so dedup keeps the join.\n   742→  //   SAFFRON case: baseHeading was the partial line; continuation logic above upgraded\n   743→  //     firstStructuralHeading to the full join. Filter removes the partial so dedup keeps join.\n   744→  // Safety: only fires when the complete heading itself is in selected (passed the threshold).\n   745→  if (firstStructuralHeading && selected.some((s) => s.text === firstStructuralHeading.text)) {\n   746→    const fshLower = firstStructuralHeading.text.toLowerCase();\n   747→    selected = selected.filter((s) => {\n   748→      if (s.text === firstStructuralHeading.text) return true;\n   749→      const sLower = s.text.toLowerCase();\n   750→      // Remove s if it is a space-delimited prefix of the structural heading\n   751→      return !fshLower.startsWith(sLower + \" \");\n   752→    });\n   753→  }\n   754→\n   755→  // Protect continuation joins: when a multi-line join (2-line or 3-line) survived the threshold\n   756→  // and its second part starts with a continuation character, remove the single-line prefix/suffix\n   757→  // so the dedup \"shorter wins\" rule doesn't destroy the complete join.\n   758→  // Note: the pre-merge step above already handles the common Baked Eggs case (&/continuation\n   759→  // on next line) by turning it into a single candidate — this block covers the rarer case where\n   760→  // a continuation-character join was generated as a 2-line/3-line candidate and the prefix\n   761→  // single also survived threshold independently (e.g. from a different code path or OCR layout).\n   762→  // Safety: only fires for joins whose continuation starts with /&+:( — digit continuations\n   763→  // like \"Pierogi Ruskie 200g mąki\" are NOT protected, so dedup correctly keeps the shorter form.\n   764→  const survivingJoins = selected.filter((s) => s.origin === \"2-line\" || s.origin === \"3-line\");\n   765→  if (survivingJoins.length > 0) {\n   766→    selected = selected.filter((s) => {\n   767→      if (s.origin !== \"single\") return true;\n   768→      const sLower = s.text.toLowerCase();\n   769→      // Remove PREFIX singles whose continuation join also survived\n   770→      const isPrefixOfJoin = survivingJoins.some((j) => {\n   771→        const jLower = j.text.toLowerCase();\n   772→        if (!jLower.startsWith(sLower + \" \")) return false;\n   773→        const remainder = jLower.slice(sLower.length + 1);\n   774→        return /^[/&+:(]/.test(remainder);\n   775→      });\n   776→      if (isPrefixOfJoin) return false;\n   777→      // Remove SUFFIX singles (e.g. \"& Coriander\") whose parent join also survived\n   778→      const isSuffixOfJoin = survivingJoins.some((j) => {\n   779→        const jLower = j.text.toLowerCase();\n   780→        if (!jLower.endsWith(\" \" + sLower)) return false;\n   781→        // Only remove if the suffix starts with a continuation character\n   782→        return /^[/&+:(]/.test(sLower);\n   783→      });\n   784→      if (isSuffixOfJoin) return false;\n   785→      return true;\n   786→    });\n   787→  }\n   788→\n   789→  // Pre-dedup: remove sub-section headers that are substrings of other surviving candidates.\n   790→  // A sub-section header is an ALL_CAPS candidate followed by ingredient-like lines in the source.\n   791→  // Example: \"CHLEBEK\" (bread section header, followed by \"500 g mąki\") is a substring of\n   792→  // \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" (the real title). Without this filter, dedup kills the title.\n   793→  selected = selected.filter((candidate) => {\n   794→    if (!isAllCaps(candidate.text)) return true;\n   795→    // Check if this candidate is immediately followed by ingredient-like content\n   796→    const nextSourceLines = lines.slice(candidate.position + 1, candidate.position + 2);\n   797→    const followedByIngredients = nextSourceLines.some(\n   798→      (l) => looksLikeIngredient(l.trim()) || startsWithNumber(l.trim())\n   799→    );\n   800→    if (!followedByIngredients) return true;\n   801→    // Only remove if a longer candidate contains this one as a substring\n   802→    const candidateLower = candidate.text.toLowerCase();\n   803→    const hasLongerParent = rawScored.some(\n   804→      (other) =>\n   805→        other.text !== candidate.text &&\n   806→        other.text.length > candidate.text.length &&\n   807→        other.text.toLowerCase().includes(candidateLower)\n   808→    );\n   809→    return !hasLongerParent;\n   810→  });\n   811→\n   812→  // Protect multi-line joins from being destroyed by their own component singles.\n   813→  // When \"Lamb Stew\" (2-line join) survives AND both \"Lamb\" and \"Stew\" (singles) also survive,\n   814→  // the join is the intended title — remove the singles.\n   815→  const joinsToProtect = selected.filter((s) => s.origin === \"2-line\" || s.origin === \"3-line\");\n   816→  if (joinsToProtect.length > 0) {\n   817→    const singlesToRemove = new Set<string>();\n   818→    for (const join of joinsToProtect) {\n   819→      const joinWords = join.text.split(/\\s+/);\n   820→      const componentSingles = selected.filter(\n   821→        (s) => s.origin === \"single\" && joinWords.some((w) => s.text.toLowerCase() === w.toLowerCase())\n   822→      );\n   823→      if (componentSingles.length >= Math.min(joinWords.length, 2)) {\n   824→        componentSingles.forEach((s) => singlesToRemove.add(s.text));\n   825→      }\n   826→    }\n   827→    if (singlesToRemove.size > 0) {\n   828→      selected = selected.filter((s) => s.origin !== \"single\" || !singlesToRemove.has(s.text));\n   829→    }\n   830→  }\n   831→\n   832→  // Protect position-0 compound titles from distant sub-section headers.\n   833→  // When a position-0 compound title is longer and contains a shorter candidate\n   834→  // that appears > 10 lines later, remove the distant candidate so the dedup\n   835→  // (shorter-wins rule) doesn't destroy the compound title.\n   836→  const pos0Compounds = selected.filter((s) => s.position === 0);\n   837→  if (pos0Compounds.length > 0) {\n   838→    selected = selected.filter((s) => {\n   839→      if (s.position === 0) return true;\n   840→      const sLower = s.text.toLowerCase();\n   841→      return !pos0Compounds.some(\n   842→        (p0) =>\n   843→          p0.position + 10 < s.position &&\n   844→          s.text.length < p0.text.length &&\n   845→          p0.text.toLowerCase().includes(sLower)\n   846→      );\n   847→    });\n   848→  }\n   849→\n   850→  // Deduplicate: if one title is a substring of another, keep the shorter (more focused) one.\n   851→  // DO NOT CHANGE THIS LOGIC — it has been incorrectly \"improved\" by the title-loop 5 times.\n   852→  // The tests require shorter wins: \"Pierogi Ruskie\" over \"Pierogi Ruskie 200g mąki 3 ziemniaki\".\n   853→  // The pre-filter above handles the conflicting case (structural heading prefix removal) so that\n   854→  // the incomplete prefix line is never present here when the complete join is in selected.\n   855→  selected = selected.filter((a) => {\n   856→    const aLower = a.text.toLowerCase();\n   857→    return !selected.some(\n   858→      (b) =>\n   859→        b !== a &&\n   860→        aLower.includes(b.text.toLowerCase()) &&\n   861→        b.text.length < a.text.length\n   862→    );\n   863→  });\n   864→\n   865→  // Multi-title guard: only join multiple candidates with \"+\" when there is\n   866→  // structural evidence of a multi-recipe page (≥2 ALL_CAPS headings).\n   867→  // A single ALL_CAPS title among mixed-case survivors is a single-recipe page —\n   868→  // collapse to the highest-scoring candidate.\n   869→  // Zero ALL_CAPS survivors → apply positional tiebreak only when candidates are\n   870→  // spread far apart (>10 lines), which indicates body-text leakage. Closely-\n   871→  // positioned candidates are likely genuine multi-recipe content.\n   872→  if (selected.length > 1) {\n   873→    const allCapsSelected = selected.filter((s) => isAllCaps(s.text));\n   874→    if (allCapsSelected.length >= 2) {\n   875→      // Check whether non-first ALL_CAPS headings are section headers within one recipe\n   876→      // (followed immediately by ingredient-like content) rather than separate recipe titles.\n   877→      // A multi-recipe page has body text between titles; a single-recipe page has\n   878→      // ingredient lines immediately after each section heading.\n   879→      const sortedCaps = [...allCapsSelected].sort((a, b) => a.position - b.position);\n   880→      const isSubHeader = sortedCaps.slice(1).every((cap) => {\n   881→        const nextLines = lines.slice(cap.position + 1, cap.position + 3);\n   882→        return nextLines.some(\n   883→          (l) => looksLikeIngredient(l.trim()) || /^\\s*\\d/.test(l.trim())\n   884→        );\n   885→      });\n   886→      if (isSubHeader) {\n   887→        selected = [sortedCaps[0]];\n   888→      } else {\n   889→        selected = allCapsSelected;\n   890→      }\n   891→    } else if (allCapsSelected.length === 1) {\n   892→      const theCapCandidate = allCapsSelected[0];\n   893→      // Use non-empty line count so the 75% threshold is consistent regardless of blank-line density.\n   894→      const nonEmptyCount = lines.filter((l) => l.trim().length > 0).length;\n   895→      const capRelPos = theCapCandidate.position / Math.max(nonEmptyCount, 1);\n   896→      // If the sole ALL_CAPS candidate is in the last 25% of the document,\n   897→      // it's likely a category footer, not a title. Prefer the best earlier candidate.\n   898→      if (capRelPos > 0.75) {\n   899→        const earlierCandidates = selected.filter(\n   900→          (s) => s.position / Math.max(nonEmptyCount, 1) <= 0.75\n   901→        );\n   902→        if (earlierCandidates.length > 0) {\n   903→          selected = [earlierCandidates.reduce((a, b) => (a.score > b.score ? a : b))];\n   904→        } else {\n   905→          // All candidates are in the last 25% — no positional basis to prefer one over another;\n   906→          // fall back to score, accepting that the guard cannot help here.\n   907→          selected = [selected.reduce((a, b) => (a.score > b.score ? a : b))];\n   908→        }\n   909→      } else {\n   910→        selected = [selected.reduce((a, b) => (a.score > b.score ? a : b))];\n   911→      }\n   912→    } else {\n   913→      // Zero ALL_CAPS survivors → mixed-case page.\n   914→      // If all survivors are closely positioned (within 10 lines of each other), keep them all —\n   915→      // they're likely genuine multi-recipe content on a single page.\n   916→      // If any survivor is far from the earliest, apply a positional tiebreak: the real title\n   917→      // is almost always the earliest candidate; distant survivors are likely body-text leakage.\n   918→      selected.sort((a, b) => a.position - b.position);\n   919→      const earliest = selected[0];\n   920→      const farthest = selected[selected.length - 1];\n   921→      if (farthest.position - earliest.position > 10) {\n   922→        const closeCompetitors = selected.filter(\n   923→          (s) => s.position <= earliest.position + 3 && s.score > earliest.score\n   924→        );\n   925→        selected = closeCompetitors.length > 0\n   926→          ? [closeCompetitors.reduce((a, b) => (a.score > b.score ? a : b))]\n   927→          : [earliest];\n   928→      }\n   929→    }\n   930→  }\n   931→\n   932→  // Cap at 3, sort by document position\n   933→  selected.sort((a, b) => a.position - b.position);\n   934→  selected = selected.slice(0, 3);\n   935→\n   936→  if (selected.length === 0) {\n   937→    return undefined;\n   938→  }\n   939→\n   940→  return selected.map((s) => s.text).join(\" + \");\n   941→}\n   942→\n   943→/**\n   944→ * Extract potential recipe title from OCR text (sync heuristic fallback)\n   945→ */\n   946→export function extractTitle(text: string): string | undefined {\n   947→  if (!text || text.trim().length === 0) {\n   948→    return undefined;\n   949→  }\n   950→\n   951→  const lines = text.split(\"\\n\").map((line) => line.trim());\n   952→\n   953→  for (const line of lines) {\n   954→    if (line.length === 0) continue;\n   955→    if (line.length < 3 || line.length > 50) continue;\n   956→    if (looksLikeIngredient(line)) continue;\n   957→    if (isAllCaps(line)) continue;\n   958→    if (startsWithNumber(line)) continue;\n   959→    return line;\n   960→  }\n   961→\n   962→  return undefined;\n   963→}\n   964→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01FwmSUB7BcKRiNUxc3Y5dsK","session_id":"8522d0c9-fb93-4365-9c6c-c3c9ffbbbc7e","uuid":"3c2018f6-c757-42b8-84c5-4f717bedb3ea"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01SLz9CcPmBQ9QJiinkAsfHL","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→import {\n     2→  extractTitle,\n     3→  extractTitleWithEmbeddings,\n     4→  _resetEmbeddingCacheForTests,\n     5→} from \"../title-extractor\";\n     6→\n     7→/**\n     8→ * Creates a mock embed function that returns predictable vectors.\n     9→ * Words matching titleWords get a vector pointing \"toward titles\",\n    10→ * words matching headerWords get a vector pointing \"toward headers\",\n    11→ * and everything else gets a neutral vector.\n    12→ */\n    13→function createMockEmbed(\n    14→  titleWords: Array<string>,\n    15→  headerWords: Array<string>\n    16→): (text: string) => Promise<Array<number>> {\n    17→  // Reference phrases from the module\n    18→  const TITLE_REF =\n    19→    \"recipe name, dish title, name of the food, nazwa przepisu, nazwa dania\";\n    20→  const HEADER_REF =\n    21→    \"ingredients list, cooking directions, section heading, składniki, przygotowanie, sposób wykonania\";\n    22→  const NOISE_REF =\n    23→    \"page number, table of contents, book footer, garbled text\";\n    24→\n    25→  return async (text: string): Promise<Array<number>> => {\n    26→    const lower = text.toLowerCase();\n    27→\n    28→    // Title reference → unit vector in dimension 0\n    29→    if (lower === TITLE_REF.toLowerCase()) {\n    30→      return [1, 0, 0];\n    31→    }\n    32→    // Header reference → unit vector in dimension 1\n    33→    if (lower === HEADER_REF.toLowerCase()) {\n    34→      return [0, 1, 0];\n    35→    }\n    36→    // Noise reference → unit vector in dimension 2 (orthogonal)\n    37→    if (lower === NOISE_REF.toLowerCase()) {\n    38→      return [0, 0, 1];\n    39→    }\n    40→\n    41→    // Check if text contains title-like words → high cosine with title ref\n    42→    const isTitle = titleWords.some((w) => lower.includes(w.toLowerCase()));\n    43→    // Check if text contains header-like words → high cosine with header ref\n    44→    const isHeader = headerWords.some((w) => lower.includes(w.toLowerCase()));\n    45→\n    46→    if (isTitle && !isHeader) {\n    47→      return [0.9, 0.1, 0]; // High title similarity, low header similarity\n    48→    }\n    49→    if (isHeader && !isTitle) {\n    50→      return [0.1, 0.9, 0]; // Low title similarity, high header similarity\n    51→    }\n    52→    if (isTitle && isHeader) {\n    53→      return [0.5, 0.5, 0]; // Ambiguous\n    54→    }\n    55→    // Neutral\n    56→    return [0.3, 0.3, 0.7];\n    57→  };\n    58→}\n    59→\n    60→describe(\"extractTitle (heuristic)\", () => {\n    61→  it(\"returns undefined for empty text\", () => {\n    62→    expect(extractTitle(\"\")).toBeUndefined();\n    63→    expect(extractTitle(\"  \")).toBeUndefined();\n    64→  });\n    65→\n    66→  it(\"returns the first valid line\", () => {\n    67→    expect(extractTitle(\"Chicken Soup\\nIngredients\\n1 cup water\")).toBe(\n    68→      \"Chicken Soup\"\n    69→    );\n    70→  });\n    71→\n    72→  it(\"skips lines that are too short or too long\", () => {\n    73→    const longLine = \"A\".repeat(51);\n    74→    expect(extractTitle(`ab\\n${longLine}\\nGood Title`)).toBe(\"Good Title\");\n    75→  });\n    76→\n    77→  it(\"skips ingredient lines\", () => {\n    78→    expect(extractTitle(\"2 cups flour\\nApple Pie\")).toBe(\"Apple Pie\");\n    79→  });\n    80→\n    81→  it(\"skips all-caps lines\", () => {\n    82→    expect(extractTitle(\"INGREDIENTS\\nChocolate Cake\")).toBe(\"Chocolate Cake\");\n    83→  });\n    84→\n    85→  it(\"skips lines starting with numbers\", () => {\n    86→    expect(extractTitle(\"12\\nApple Pie\")).toBe(\"Apple Pie\");\n    87→  });\n    88→});\n    89→\n    90→describe(\"extractTitleWithEmbeddings\", () => {\n    91→  beforeEach(() => {\n    92→    _resetEmbeddingCacheForTests();\n    93→  });\n    94→\n    95→  it(\"returns undefined for empty text\", async () => {\n    96→    const embed = createMockEmbed([], []);\n    97→    expect(await extractTitleWithEmbeddings(\"\", embed)).toBeUndefined();\n    98→    expect(await extractTitleWithEmbeddings(\"  \", embed)).toBeUndefined();\n    99→  });\n   100→\n   101→  it(\"picks title over section header (Polish)\", async () => {\n   102→    const embed = createMockEmbed([\"pierogi ruskie\"], [\"składniki\"]);\n   103→    const text = \"Składniki\\nPierogi Ruskie\\n200g mąki\\n3 ziemniaki\";\n   104→    const result = await extractTitleWithEmbeddings(text, embed);\n   105→    expect(result).toBe(\"Pierogi Ruskie\");\n   106→  });\n   107→\n   108→  it(\"picks title over section header (English)\", async () => {\n   109→    const embed = createMockEmbed([\"chicken soup\"], [\"ingredients\"]);\n   110→    const text = \"Ingredients\\nChicken Soup\\n1 cup water\\nSalt\";\n   111→    const result = await extractTitleWithEmbeddings(text, embed);\n   112→    expect(result).toBe(\"Chicken Soup\");\n   113→  });\n   114→\n   115→  it(\"preserves all-caps titles\", async () => {\n   116→    const embed = createMockEmbed([\"chocolate cake\"], [\"ingredients\"]);\n   117→    const text = \"CHOCOLATE CAKE\\nIngredients\\n200g flour\";\n   118→    const result = await extractTitleWithEmbeddings(text, embed);\n   119→    expect(result).toBe(\"CHOCOLATE CAKE\");\n   120→  });\n   121→\n   122→  it(\"skips numbered lines\", async () => {\n   123→    const embed = createMockEmbed([\"apple pie\"], []);\n   124→    const text = \"12\\nApple Pie\\nSome instructions\";\n   125→    const result = await extractTitleWithEmbeddings(text, embed);\n   126→    expect(result).toBe(\"Apple Pie\");\n   127→  });\n   128→\n   129→  it(\"joins multi-line title (2 lines)\", async () => {\n   130→    const embed = createMockEmbed(\n   131→      [\"kurczak w sosie śmietanowym z pieczarkami\"],\n   132→      [\"składniki\"]\n   133→    );\n   134→    const text =\n   135→      \"Kurczak w sosie\\nśmietanowym z pieczarkami\\nSkładniki\\n200g kurczaka\";\n   136→    const result = await extractTitleWithEmbeddings(text, embed);\n   137→    expect(result).toBe(\"Kurczak w sosie śmietanowym z pieczarkami\");\n   138→  });\n   139→\n   140→  it(\"joins multi-line title (3 lines)\", async () => {\n   141→    const embed = createMockEmbed(\n   142→      [\"makaron z sosem pomidorowym i bazylią\"],\n   143→      [\"składniki\"]\n   144→    );\n   145→    const text =\n   146→      \"Makaron z sosem\\npomidorowym\\ni bazylią\\nSkładniki\\n300g makaronu\";\n   147→    const result = await extractTitleWithEmbeddings(text, embed);\n   148→    expect(result).toBe(\"Makaron z sosem pomidorowym i bazylią\");\n   149→  });\n   150→\n   151→  it(\"does not over-greedily join title with header\", async () => {\n   152→    const embed = createMockEmbed([\"apple pie\"], [\"ingredients\"]);\n   153→    const text = \"Apple Pie\\nIngredients\\n200g flour\";\n   154→    const result = await extractTitleWithEmbeddings(text, embed);\n   155→    // Should prefer \"Apple Pie\" alone, not \"Apple Pie Ingredients\"\n   156→    expect(result).toBe(\"Apple Pie\");\n   157→  });\n   158→\n   159→  it(\"returns multiple titles joined with + when both score well\", async () => {\n   160→    const embed = createMockEmbed(\n   161→      [\"first recipe\", \"second recipe\"],\n   162→      []\n   163→    );\n   164→    const text = \"First Recipe\\nSecond Recipe\\nSome other text\";\n   165→    const result = await extractTitleWithEmbeddings(text, embed);\n   166→    expect(result).toBe(\"First Recipe + Second Recipe\");\n   167→  });\n   168→\n   169→  it(\"skips burst of short lines at start and finds title after\", async () => {\n   170→    const embed = createMockEmbed([\"beef stew\"], [\"ingredients\"]);\n   171→    // 3+ short garbled lines at start, then real content with a long line\n   172→    const text =\n   173→      \"pg 42\\nA.\\nfoo\\nThis is a longer line that triggers burst end detection\\nBeef Stew\\nIngredients\\n500g beef\";\n   174→    const result = await extractTitleWithEmbeddings(text, embed);\n   175→    expect(result).toBe(\"Beef Stew\");\n   176→  });\n   177→\n   178→  it(\"two titles deep in text returns both joined\", async () => {\n   179→    const embed = createMockEmbed(\n   180→      [\"pasta carbonara\", \"tiramisu classico\"],\n   181→      [\"ingredients\", \"składniki\"]\n   182→    );\n   183→    const text =\n   184→      \"Ingredients\\nPasta Carbonara\\n200g pasta\\n100g guanciale\\nIngredients\\nTiramisu Classico\\n250g mascarpone\";\n   185→    const result = await extractTitleWithEmbeddings(text, embed);\n   186→    expect(result).toBe(\"Pasta Carbonara + Tiramisu Classico\");\n   187→  });\n   188→\n   189→  it(\"single-recipe page still returns one title\", async () => {\n   190→    const embed = createMockEmbed([\"tomato soup\"], [\"ingredients\"]);\n   191→    const text = \"Tomato Soup\\nIngredients\\n4 tomatoes\\n1 cup cream\\nSalt\";\n   192→    const result = await extractTitleWithEmbeddings(text, embed);\n   193→    expect(result).toBe(\"Tomato Soup\");\n   194→  });\n   195→\n   196→  it(\"keeps 2-word ALL_CAPS join over its single-word prefix (ARAYES-type)\", async () => {\n   197→    // \"ARAYES\" alone is 1 word → never qualifies as firstStructuralHeading.\n   198→    // \"ARAYES SHRAK\" qualifies → pre-filter removes \"ARAYES\" so dedup keeps the join.\n   199→    const embed = createMockEmbed([\"arayes\"], [\"ingredients\"]);\n   200→    const text = \"ARAYES\\nSHRAK\\nIngredients\\n2 cups flour\";\n   201→    const result = await extractTitleWithEmbeddings(text, embed);\n   202→    expect(result).toBe(\"ARAYES SHRAK\");\n   203→  });\n   204→\n   205→  it(\"extends ALL_CAPS structural heading when next line starts with continuation token (SAFFRON-type)\", async () => {\n   206→    // \"TITLE FIRST PART\" qualifies as structural heading; continuation upgrades it to the join.\n   207→    // Pre-filter then removes the partial so dedup keeps the complete join.\n   208→    const embed = createMockEmbed([\"title first part\"], [\"ingredients\"]);\n   209→    const text = \"TITLE FIRST PART\\n/ SECOND PART\\nIngredients\\n1 cup flour\";\n   210→    const result = await extractTitleWithEmbeddings(text, embed);\n   211→    expect(result).toBe(\"TITLE FIRST PART / SECOND PART\");\n   212→  });\n   213→\n   214→  it(\"pre-merges continuation line starting with & into preceding line (Baked Eggs type)\", async () => {\n   215→    // \"& Coriander\" starts with & so it's merged into the preceding line before candidate\n   216→    // generation — the complete title enters the pool as a single candidate.\n   217→    const embed = createMockEmbed(\n   218→      [\"baked eggs with feta\"],\n   219→      [\"ingredients\"]\n   220→    );\n   221→    const text =\n   222→      \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce\\n& Coriander\\nIngredients\\n2 eggs\";\n   223→    const result = await extractTitleWithEmbeddings(text, embed);\n   224→    expect(result).toBe(\"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\");\n   225→  });\n   226→\n   227→  it(\"does not pre-merge second line that lacks a continuation character (ARAYES-type safety)\", async () => {\n   228→    // \"SHRAK\" does not start with /&+:( so it is NOT pre-merged.\n   229→    // The existing structural heading join logic handles it instead.\n   230→    const embed = createMockEmbed([\"arayes\"], [\"ingredients\"]);\n   231→    const text = \"ARAYES\\nSHRAK\\nIngredients\\n2 cups flour\";\n   232→    const result = await extractTitleWithEmbeddings(text, embed);\n   233→    expect(result).toBe(\"ARAYES SHRAK\");\n   234→  });\n   235→\n   236→  it(\"returns only the first ALL_CAPS heading when subsequent ALL_CAPS headings are section headers followed by ingredients (CHLEBEK type)\", async () => {\n   237→    // WARZYWA I BOCZEK is immediately followed by ingredient lines (numbers) →\n   238→    // it's a section header, not a second recipe title. Keep only CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM.\n   239→    const embed = createMockEmbed(\n   240→      [\"chlebek z warzywami i boczkiem\", \"warzywa i boczek\"],\n   241→      []\n   242→    );\n   243→    const text = [\n   244→      \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\",\n   245→      \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\",\n   246→      \"500 g strączków zielonego groszku\",\n   247→      \"1 żółta papryka\",\n   248→      \"CHLEBEK\",\n   249→      \"500 g mąki\",\n   250→    ].join(\"\\n\");\n   251→    const result = await extractTitleWithEmbeddings(text, embed);\n   252→    expect(result).toBe(\"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\");\n   253→  });\n   254→\n   255→  it(\"returns both ALL_CAPS titles when headings are NOT followed by ingredient lines (FINNISH-type)\", async () => {\n   256→    // POTATO FLATBREADS is followed by body text, not ingredients →\n   257→    // these are two separate recipe titles on a multi-recipe page.\n   258→    const embed = createMockEmbed(\n   259→      [\"milk flatbreads\", \"potato flatbreads\"],\n   260→      []\n   261→    );\n   262→    const text = [\n   263→      \"MILK FLATBREADS\",\n   264→      \"Mix flour with milk and knead\",\n   265→      \"Cook on a dry skillet\",\n   266→      \"POTATO FLATBREADS\",\n   267→      \"Boil potatoes until tender\",\n   268→      \"Mash well before mixing\",\n   269→    ].join(\"\\n\");\n   270→    const result = await extractTitleWithEmbeddings(text, embed);\n   271→    expect(result).toBe(\"MILK FLATBREADS + POTATO FLATBREADS\");\n   272→  });\n   273→\n   274→  it(\"filters bullet-list lines so real title wins\", async () => {\n   275→    const embed = createMockEmbed([\"mozzarella sticks\"], []);\n   276→    const text = \"MOZZARELLA STICKS\\n- 2 tbsp sugar\\n- Salt to taste\";\n   277→    const result = await extractTitleWithEmbeddings(text, embed);\n   278→    expect(result).toBe(\"MOZZARELLA STICKS\");\n   279→  });\n   280→\n   281→  it(\"filters INGREDIENTS section label so real ALL_CAPS title wins\", async () => {\n   282→    const embed = createMockEmbed([\"mozzarella sticks\"], []);\n   283→    const text = \"INGREDIENTS\\nMOZZARELLA STICKS\\n- 2 tbsp sugar\";\n   284→    const result = await extractTitleWithEmbeddings(text, embed);\n   285→    expect(result).toBe(\"MOZZARELLA STICKS\");\n   286→  });\n   287→\n   288→  it(\"filters compact metric ingredient lines so real title wins\", async () => {\n   289→    const embed = createMockEmbed([\"barszcz czerwony\"], []);\n   290→    const text = \"BARSZCZ CZERWONY\\n100g buraków\\n50ml bulionu\";\n   291→    const result = await extractTitleWithEmbeddings(text, embed);\n   292→    expect(result).toBe(\"BARSZCZ CZERWONY\");\n   293→  });\n   294→\n   295→  it(\"prefers mixed-case title at position 0 over ALL_CAPS subtitle at position 1 (bilingual page)\", async () => {\n   296→    // \"Faszerowana papryka\" is the Polish title at position 0 (mixed-case).\n   297→    // \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" is an ALL_CAPS romanization at position 1 — treated as subtitle.\n   298→    const embed = createMockEmbed(\n   299→      [\"faszerowana papryka\", \"paprika gyeran\"],\n   300→      []\n   301→    );\n   302→    const text =\n   303→      \"Faszerowana papryka\\nPAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\\nIngredients\\n200g peppers\";\n   304→    const result = await extractTitleWithEmbeddings(text, embed);\n   305→    expect(result).toBe(\"Faszerowana papryka\");\n   306→  });\n   307→\n   308→  it(\"merges 4 consecutive short ALL_CAPS lines into one title (LABANEH-type)\", async () => {\n   309→    // Each OCR line is ≤2 words and ≤25 chars — the short-caps merge pass coalesces them.\n   310→    const embed = createMockEmbed([\"labaneh\"], []);\n   311→    const text = [\n   312→      \"LABANEH\",\n   313→      \"BALLS\",\n   314→      \"WITH NIGELLA\",\n   315→      \"SEEDS\",\n   316→      \"Essential to blending the flavours together\",\n   317→    ].join(\"\\n\");\n   318→    const result = await extractTitleWithEmbeddings(text, embed);\n   319→    expect(result).toBe(\"LABANEH BALLS WITH NIGELLA SEEDS\");\n   320→  });\n   321→\n   322→  it(\"short-caps merge breaks at a section label, preventing spurious joins\", async () => {\n   323→    // WORD ONE and WORD TWO are short ALL_CAPS, but INGREDIENTS (section label) sits between\n   324→    // them and breaks the run — they should NOT be merged into \"WORD ONE WORD TWO\".\n   325→    const embed = createMockEmbed([\"word one\"], []);\n   326→    const text = [\n   327→      \"WORD ONE\",\n   328→      \"INGREDIENTS\",\n   329→      \"WORD TWO\",\n   330→      \"Some body text here to fill the page\",\n   331→    ].join(\"\\n\");\n   332→    const result = await extractTitleWithEmbeddings(text, embed);\n   333→    // WORD ONE wins (title word); WORD TWO is a separate candidate but scores lower.\n   334→    // The key assertion: no \"WORD ONE INGREDIENTS WORD TWO\" merged result.\n   335→    expect(result).toBe(\"WORD ONE\");\n   336→  });\n   337→\n   338→  it(\"short-caps merge does not fire when a line exceeds 2 words\", async () => {\n   339→    // \"THREE WORD LINE\" has 3 words — above the ≤2 limit — so it is never the start of a merge run.\n   340→    const embed = createMockEmbed([\"three word line\"], []);\n   341→    const text = [\n   342→      \"THREE WORD LINE\",\n   343→      \"ANOTHER LINE\",\n   344→      \"Body text follows here\",\n   345→    ].join(\"\\n\");\n   346→    const result = await extractTitleWithEmbeddings(text, embed);\n   347→    // Candidates are generated individually; no spurious merge of the two lines by the caps pass.\n   348→    // \"THREE WORD LINE ANOTHER LINE\" may appear as a downstream 2-line join candidate but\n   349→    // \"THREE WORD LINE\" wins as the structural heading (more words, higher rawScore from title word).\n   350→    expect(result).toBe(\"THREE WORD LINE\");\n   351→  });\n   352→\n   353→  it(\"filters OCR-corrupted serving size 'DLA & OSOB' so mixed-case title wins\", async () => {\n   354→    // \"DLA & OSOB\" is OCR-corrupted Polish \"DLA 4 OSÓB\" (for 4 people) — metadata, not a title.\n   355→    // The expanded DLA pattern matches even when the digit is corrupted to a symbol.\n   356→    const embed = createMockEmbed([\"smażona zielona fasolka\"], []);\n   357→    const text = [\n   358→      \"Smażona zielona fasolka\",\n   359→      \"DLA & OSOB\",\n   360→      \"200g fasolki\",\n   361→      \"1 cebula\",\n   362→    ].join(\"\\n\");\n   363→    const result = await extractTitleWithEmbeddings(text, embed);\n   364→    expect(result).toBe(\"Smażona zielona fasolka\");\n   365→  });\n   366→\n   367→  it(\"layout-based bilingual detection suppresses ALL_CAPS romanization with no word overlap\", async () => {\n   368→    // Mixed-case title at position 0 (≥2 words) + ALL_CAPS candidate at position 1 with no\n   369→    // words in common → layout guard fires and suppresses the ALL_CAPS candidate.\n   370→    const embed = createMockEmbed([\"mixed case title\", \"all caps different\"], []);\n   371→    const text = [\n   372→      \"Mixed Case Title\",\n   373→      \"ALL CAPS DIFFERENT\",\n   374→      \"Body text that fills the rest of the page\",\n   375→    ].join(\"\\n\");\n   376→    const result = await extractTitleWithEmbeddings(text, embed);\n   377→    expect(result).toBe(\"Mixed Case Title\");\n   378→  });\n   379→});\n   380→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01FwmSUB7BcKRiNUxc3Y5dsK","session_id":"8522d0c9-fb93-4365-9c6c-c3c9ffbbbc7e","uuid":"3d29ceec-79c4-45e1-8035-15d2b9d17705"}
{"type":"system","subtype":"task_notification","task_id":"a835dc1423a5344d7","tool_use_id":"toolu_01FwmSUB7BcKRiNUxc3Y5dsK","status":"completed","output_file":"","summary":"Review title-extractor changes","usage":{"total_tokens":39458,"tool_uses":2,"duration_ms":61909},"uuid":"b78753ec-d17c-4d73-a36e-584522bbb533","session_id":"8522d0c9-fb93-4365-9c6c-c3c9ffbbbc7e"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01FwmSUB7BcKRiNUxc3Y5dsK","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Here is my analysis of all three changes.\n\n---\n\n# Code Review: title-extractor.ts — Three Targeted Changes\n\n## Review Metrics\n- Files Reviewed: 2\n- Critical Issues: 0\n- High Priority: 1\n- Medium Priority: 4\n- Low Priority: 2\n\n## Executive Summary\n\nAll three changes are implemented to completion and integrate cleanly with existing patterns. The main concern is a subtle logic error in the positional tiebreak (Change 2) that leaves a gap in what it actually does when `closeCompetitors` is non-empty: it picks the best-scoring one rather than keeping all close competitors as intended. There are also gaps in test coverage for all three new branches.\n\n---\n\n## HIGH Priority\n\n### 1. Position tiebreak returns one candidate but the comments say \"keep\"\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:922–928`\n\nThe comments on lines 869–871 and 915–917 say \"keep\" all close competitors when they are within 3 positions and score higher. The implementation does not do that:\n\n```typescript\nconst closeCompetitors = selected.filter(\n  (s) => s.position <= earliest.position + 3 && s.score > earliest.score\n);\nselected = closeCompetitors.length > 0\n  ? [closeCompetitors.reduce((a, b) => (a.score > b.score ? a : b))]\n  : [earliest];\n```\n\n`closeCompetitors` is filtered to multiple candidates, then immediately collapsed to one via `reduce`. The `else` path that \"preserves multi-recipe behavior\" is only reached when the span is ≤10, not in the `closeCompetitors.length > 0` branch. If the intent is that multiple close, high-scoring candidates constitute genuine multi-recipe content, then reducing to one is incorrect. If the intent is always to return exactly one title in the zero-ALL_CAPS case, the comment \"Closely-positioned candidates are likely genuine multi-recipe content\" on the span ≤10 branch is misleading because this branch never returns multiple results.\n\nDecide which behavior is intended and reconcile the code and comments. If one title is always right for zero-ALL_CAPS pages, remove the \"keep\" language from the comments. If multiple close competitors should be kept, remove the `reduce`.\n\n---\n\n## Medium Priority\n\n### 2. Word-count filter exception regex does not match its documentation\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:282`\n\n```typescript\nif (words.length >= 8 && !/ [+:&] /.test(text)) return false;\n```\n\nThe inline comment says `\" + \", \" : \", or \" & \"`. The regex `/ [+:&] /` correctly requires a space on both sides, which matches the comment. However, the comment at lines 280–281 says these are \"multi-title compounds.\" A colon with spaces (` : `) is used in some of the test-input filenames (e.g., `CARAMELIZED ONION TART : VEGETARIAN VERSION`, `PIEROGI Z KAPUSTY : PIEROGI Z MIĘSEM`) which are exactly 7 words, so they pass without needing the exception. But if a colon-separated compound ever reaches 8+ words, the exception fires. Verify this is genuinely the intended behavior for colon-separated titles and not an accidental inclusion of `:` from the separator pattern used elsewhere in the codebase. The ` : ` pattern for multi-title pages uses ` + ` or ` & ` throughout the rest of the pipeline, not ` : `, so its presence here is surprising.\n\n### 3. `POLISH_COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS` has a capitalisation inconsistency\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:250`\n\n```\nwymiesza[jJ]|miesza[jJ]\n```\n\nThese two alternatives have explicit `[jJ]` character classes while every other verb in the same regex uses lowercase with the `/i` flag at the end covering both cases. The `[jJ]` classes are harmless but inconsistent and suggest a copy/paste artifact. They can be simplified to `wymieszaj|mieszaj` since the trailing `/i` already handles the uppercase `J`.\n\n### 4. Positional tiebreak does not cap at 3 or sort before returning\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:918–928`\n\nIn the `farthest.position - earliest.position > 10` branch, the code sets `selected` to a single-element array and then falls through to the shared `selected.sort(...)` and `selected.slice(0, 3)` at lines 933–934. That is fine. But in the `≤10` branch (no early return, `selected` is not reassigned), the existing array falls through as-is — which is also fine. The flow is correct, but there is no comment noting that the ≤10 path intentionally falls through to the shared cap-and-sort. Given how much other logic in this function has explanatory comments, a brief note here would reduce the risk of a future change accidentally re-sorting or resetting `selected` before this block runs.\n\n### 5. No tests for any of the three new branches\n\nAll 33 tests pass, but none of them exercise the three new code paths:\n\n- `POLISH_COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS`: no test sends a Polish imperative instruction as a candidate and asserts it is excluded. The only cooking-instruction tests appear to be implicit (the verb list is never an explicit test boundary).\n- Position-based tiebreak for zero-ALL_CAPS: the `else` branch at line 912 is entirely untested. The existing test \"returns multiple titles joined with + when both score well\" (line 159) hits this block only if both titles are mixed-case and within 10 lines, which exercises the ≤10 pass-through rather than the `>10` tiebreak.\n- Word count filter: no test verifies that an 8-word plain line is rejected, nor that an 8-word line with ` + ` is accepted.\n\nThese are medium rather than high because the tests are for a research/iteration loop, but the risk of silent regression is real. The positional tiebreak in particular has non-trivial branching that is easy to accidentally break.\n\n---\n\n## Low Priority\n\n### 6. `closeCompetitors` filter condition is position-first, score-second — but `earliest` may not be the best early candidate\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:922–924`\n\n```typescript\nconst closeCompetitors = selected.filter(\n  (s) => s.position <= earliest.position + 3 && s.score > earliest.score\n);\n```\n\n`earliest` is the positionally first candidate after `selected.sort(...)`. If there are two candidates at positions 0 and 1, and a third at position 20, then `earliest` is the position-0 one. A close competitor must beat `earliest.score`. This is reasonable but the behavior when the position-0 candidate has a much lower score than the position-1 candidate (which is within 3) is that the position-1 one is placed in `closeCompetitors` and returned alone, while the position-0 one is dropped. That might be the desired outcome (higher-scoring close competitor beats earliest), but it silently discards the earliest. The comment says \"keeping only the earliest or a close higher-scoring competitor\" — so this appears intentional, but it is worth verifying that dropping `earliest` when a close higher-scoring competitor exists is the intended behavior.\n\n### 7. `looksLikeCookingInstruction` minimum word threshold silently neutralises the Polish regex for short imperative lines\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:253–257`\n\n```typescript\nconst words = text.trim().split(/\\s+/);\nif (words.length < 4) return false;\nif (COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS.test(text.trim())) return true;\nif (POLISH_COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS.test(text.trim())) return true;\n```\n\nA 3-word Polish instruction such as \"Dodaj cebulę sól\" would pass the hard filters (3 words, passes length check, not an ingredient, not metadata) despite matching the Polish regex, because `words.length < 4` returns false early. The existing minimum-word guard predates the Polish regex and was designed for English instructions which tend to be longer. Polish instructions are often shorter due to synthetic verb forms. This may be intentional if you want to preserve short Polish imperative forms as potential title fragments, but is worth a deliberate decision rather than an accidental interaction.\n\n---\n\n## Strengths\n\n- The `POLISH_COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS` regex comment explains the `Piecz` exclusion explicitly — that is exactly the level of detail needed for a non-obvious decision.\n- The tiebreak for the zero-ALL_CAPS case correctly sorts before computing `earliest` and `farthest`, so position comparisons are correct.\n- The word-count filter's separator exception reuses the existing convention for compound multi-recipe titles (` + `, ` & `) rather than introducing a new pattern.\n- The comment block on lines 869–871 that precedes the multi-title guard summarizes all three branches before the code — a good documentation pattern given the complexity."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a835dc1423a5344d7 (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 41754\ntool_uses: 2\nduration_ms: 61913</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8522d0c9-fb93-4365-9c6c-c3c9ffbbbc7e","uuid":"66108f0a-6db9-428e-b021-a769db17d22d","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Review the following changes to `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`. Focus on these specific aspects:\n\n1. **Implementation Completeness** — Are the three changes fully implemented as described in the plan, or is anything half-done?\n2. **Code Quality** — Are there any issues with the new code (bugs, edge cases, readability)?\n3. **Integration** — Is the new code integrated properly or just bolted on?\n4. **Codebase Consistency** — Should anything else be updated (tests, comments, docs)?\n\n## Change 1: Polish cooking instruction filter\nAdded `POLISH_COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS` regex constant and updated `looksLikeCookingInstruction` to check it.\n\n## Change 2: Position-based tiebreak for zero-ALL_CAPS multi-candidate case\nAdded an `else` branch to the multi-title guard. When zero ALL_CAPS candidates survive and the position span between earliest and farthest candidate exceeds 10 lines, it applies a positional tiebreak (keeping only the earliest or a close higher-scoring competitor within 3 positions). When span ≤ 10, all candidates are kept (preserves multi-recipe behavior).\n\n## Change 3: Word count filter in passesHardFilters\nLines with ≥8 words are rejected unless they contain ` + `, ` : `, or ` & ` separators.\n\nThe updated file is at `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`.\nThe tests are at `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/__tests__/title-extractor.test.ts`.\nAll 33 tests pass.\n\nPlease read both files and give specific, actionable feedback on any issues found.","agentId":"a835dc1423a5344d7","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Here is my analysis of all three changes.\n\n---\n\n# Code Review: title-extractor.ts — Three Targeted Changes\n\n## Review Metrics\n- Files Reviewed: 2\n- Critical Issues: 0\n- High Priority: 1\n- Medium Priority: 4\n- Low Priority: 2\n\n## Executive Summary\n\nAll three changes are implemented to completion and integrate cleanly with existing patterns. The main concern is a subtle logic error in the positional tiebreak (Change 2) that leaves a gap in what it actually does when `closeCompetitors` is non-empty: it picks the best-scoring one rather than keeping all close competitors as intended. There are also gaps in test coverage for all three new branches.\n\n---\n\n## HIGH Priority\n\n### 1. Position tiebreak returns one candidate but the comments say \"keep\"\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:922–928`\n\nThe comments on lines 869–871 and 915–917 say \"keep\" all close competitors when they are within 3 positions and score higher. The implementation does not do that:\n\n```typescript\nconst closeCompetitors = selected.filter(\n  (s) => s.position <= earliest.position + 3 && s.score > earliest.score\n);\nselected = closeCompetitors.length > 0\n  ? [closeCompetitors.reduce((a, b) => (a.score > b.score ? a : b))]\n  : [earliest];\n```\n\n`closeCompetitors` is filtered to multiple candidates, then immediately collapsed to one via `reduce`. The `else` path that \"preserves multi-recipe behavior\" is only reached when the span is ≤10, not in the `closeCompetitors.length > 0` branch. If the intent is that multiple close, high-scoring candidates constitute genuine multi-recipe content, then reducing to one is incorrect. If the intent is always to return exactly one title in the zero-ALL_CAPS case, the comment \"Closely-positioned candidates are likely genuine multi-recipe content\" on the span ≤10 branch is misleading because this branch never returns multiple results.\n\nDecide which behavior is intended and reconcile the code and comments. If one title is always right for zero-ALL_CAPS pages, remove the \"keep\" language from the comments. If multiple close competitors should be kept, remove the `reduce`.\n\n---\n\n## Medium Priority\n\n### 2. Word-count filter exception regex does not match its documentation\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:282`\n\n```typescript\nif (words.length >= 8 && !/ [+:&] /.test(text)) return false;\n```\n\nThe inline comment says `\" + \", \" : \", or \" & \"`. The regex `/ [+:&] /` correctly requires a space on both sides, which matches the comment. However, the comment at lines 280–281 says these are \"multi-title compounds.\" A colon with spaces (` : `) is used in some of the test-input filenames (e.g., `CARAMELIZED ONION TART : VEGETARIAN VERSION`, `PIEROGI Z KAPUSTY : PIEROGI Z MIĘSEM`) which are exactly 7 words, so they pass without needing the exception. But if a colon-separated compound ever reaches 8+ words, the exception fires. Verify this is genuinely the intended behavior for colon-separated titles and not an accidental inclusion of `:` from the separator pattern used elsewhere in the codebase. The ` : ` pattern for multi-title pages uses ` + ` or ` & ` throughout the rest of the pipeline, not ` : `, so its presence here is surprising.\n\n### 3. `POLISH_COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS` has a capitalisation inconsistency\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:250`\n\n```\nwymiesza[jJ]|miesza[jJ]\n```\n\nThese two alternatives have explicit `[jJ]` character classes while every other verb in the same regex uses lowercase with the `/i` flag at the end covering both cases. The `[jJ]` classes are harmless but inconsistent and suggest a copy/paste artifact. They can be simplified to `wymieszaj|mieszaj` since the trailing `/i` already handles the uppercase `J`.\n\n### 4. Positional tiebreak does not cap at 3 or sort before returning\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:918–928`\n\nIn the `farthest.position - earliest.position > 10` branch, the code sets `selected` to a single-element array and then falls through to the shared `selected.sort(...)` and `selected.slice(0, 3)` at lines 933–934. That is fine. But in the `≤10` branch (no early return, `selected` is not reassigned), the existing array falls through as-is — which is also fine. The flow is correct, but there is no comment noting that the ≤10 path intentionally falls through to the shared cap-and-sort. Given how much other logic in this function has explanatory comments, a brief note here would reduce the risk of a future change accidentally re-sorting or resetting `selected` before this block runs.\n\n### 5. No tests for any of the three new branches\n\nAll 33 tests pass, but none of them exercise the three new code paths:\n\n- `POLISH_COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS`: no test sends a Polish imperative instruction as a candidate and asserts it is excluded. The only cooking-instruction tests appear to be implicit (the verb list is never an explicit test boundary).\n- Position-based tiebreak for zero-ALL_CAPS: the `else` branch at line 912 is entirely untested. The existing test \"returns multiple titles joined with + when both score well\" (line 159) hits this block only if both titles are mixed-case and within 10 lines, which exercises the ≤10 pass-through rather than the `>10` tiebreak.\n- Word count filter: no test verifies that an 8-word plain line is rejected, nor that an 8-word line with ` + ` is accepted.\n\nThese are medium rather than high because the tests are for a research/iteration loop, but the risk of silent regression is real. The positional tiebreak in particular has non-trivial branching that is easy to accidentally break.\n\n---\n\n## Low Priority\n\n### 6. `closeCompetitors` filter condition is position-first, score-second — but `earliest` may not be the best early candidate\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:922–924`\n\n```typescript\nconst closeCompetitors = selected.filter(\n  (s) => s.position <= earliest.position + 3 && s.score > earliest.score\n);\n```\n\n`earliest` is the positionally first candidate after `selected.sort(...)`. If there are two candidates at positions 0 and 1, and a third at position 20, then `earliest` is the position-0 one. A close competitor must beat `earliest.score`. This is reasonable but the behavior when the position-0 candidate has a much lower score than the position-1 candidate (which is within 3) is that the position-1 one is placed in `closeCompetitors` and returned alone, while the position-0 one is dropped. That might be the desired outcome (higher-scoring close competitor beats earliest), but it silently discards the earliest. The comment says \"keeping only the earliest or a close higher-scoring competitor\" — so this appears intentional, but it is worth verifying that dropping `earliest` when a close higher-scoring competitor exists is the intended behavior.\n\n### 7. `looksLikeCookingInstruction` minimum word threshold silently neutralises the Polish regex for short imperative lines\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:253–257`\n\n```typescript\nconst words = text.trim().split(/\\s+/);\nif (words.length < 4) return false;\nif (COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS.test(text.trim())) return true;\nif (POLISH_COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS.test(text.trim())) return true;\n```\n\nA 3-word Polish instruction such as \"Dodaj cebulę sól\" would pass the hard filters (3 words, passes length check, not an ingredient, not metadata) despite matching the Polish regex, because `words.length < 4` returns false early. The existing minimum-word guard predates the Polish regex and was designed for English instructions which tend to be longer. Polish instructions are often shorter due to synthetic verb forms. This may be intentional if you want to preserve short Polish imperative forms as potential title fragments, but is worth a deliberate decision rather than an accidental interaction.\n\n---\n\n## Strengths\n\n- The `POLISH_COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS` regex comment explains the `Piecz` exclusion explicitly — that is exactly the level of detail needed for a non-obvious decision.\n- The tiebreak for the zero-ALL_CAPS case correctly sorts before computing `earliest` and `farthest`, so position comparisons are correct.\n- The word-count filter's separator exception reuses the existing convention for compound multi-recipe titles (` + `, ` & `) rather than introducing a new pattern.\n- The comment block on lines 869–871 that precedes the multi-title guard summarizes all three branches before the code — a good documentation pattern given the complexity."}],"totalDurationMs":61913,"totalTokens":41754,"totalToolUseCount":2,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":23708,"cache_read_input_tokens":15745,"output_tokens":2300,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":23708},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}}}
